As shown in Fig. 6c, CIP degradation decreased slightly in 30 min in the presence of cations. However, cations exhibited a more detrimental effect on TOC removal efficiency, reducing from 90 to 65, 59, 55, and 50% in the existence of Na+, K+, Ca2+, Mg2+, respectively, in 30 min. Obviously, cations competed with CIP for surface-active sites on the catalyst thereby decreasing the CIP degradation efficiency. The influencing level of cations was in order: Na+ < K+ < Ca2+ < Mg2+ (Fig. 6d). It can be seen that the inhibitory effect of cations increased with the increase in oxidation state of the cation per sec. Importantly, according to Coulomb law, electrostatic attraction between of the hydroxyl group on the surface of catalyst and divalent cations (Mg2+ and Ca2+) was much stronger than that toward monovalent cations due to more competitive adsorption of divalent cations on the surface of catalyst with hydroxyl functional groups (
                              Fig. S7
                           ). Surface coverage of cations on the catalyst may hinder ozone decomposing into ROS and the deactivation of the catalyst [24,25].

Toxicity Estimation Software Tool (TEST) was used to estimate the toxicity of CIP and its intermediate products using Quantitative Structure-Activity Relationships (QSARs) methodologies. The USEPA toxicity test was presented in terms of LC50 (96 h) for fathead minnow, LC50 (48 h) for Daphnia magna, Amese mutagenicity and Developmental toxicity (
                           Table S4 and S5
                        ). Results showed that the LC50 (fathead minnow, 96 h) was 0.19, 0.23, 0.61, 0.48, and 0.38 mg L-1 for CIP, PI, P4, P5, and P6, respectively, which demonstrated that the above intermediates have higher fathead minnow toxicity than CIP. However, three byproducts, namely, P2 (0.14 mg L-1), P3 (0.042 mg L-1), and P7 (0.38 mg L-1) exhibited lower fathead minnow toxicity than ICO. The Daphnia magna toxicity of all intermediates was less than that of CIP. Results of Ames mutagenicity test predicted that except P2 and P3, CIP and other intermediates exhibit positive bacterial mutagenicity. Results predicted that CIP and all intermediates may be teratogenic with developmental toxicity on humans or animals.
